{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_9","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc 'rg -n \"surface_simulated|skeleton_simulated|point_simulated|morphology|hybrid\" src tests docs'","aggregated_output":"docs/milestones.md:9:Build a connectome-constrained fruit fly visual simulation where selected neurons carry **surface-wave dynamics** across their morphology, driven by a **synthetic visual scene generator**, and presented through a strong **interactive UI / analysis layer**.\ndocs/milestones.md:97:| 11 | Add hybrid morphology classes | Shared leaning programming (60/40) | Jack lead | Surface / skeleton / point neuron mix |\ndocs/milestones.md:123:**In a connectome-constrained Drosophila visual motion circuit, adding a morphology-resolved surface state should produce small but reproducible, geometry-dependent departures in shared circuit observables relative to fair point/reduced-neuron baselines.**\ndocs/milestones.md:130:* surface-localized inputs on explicit T4/T5 morphology regions  \ndocs/milestones.md:131:* surface propagation over a morphology graph  \ndocs/milestones.md:151: In a connectome-constrained Drosophila visual motion circuit, adding a morphology-resolved surface state should produce small but reproducible, geometry-dependent departures in shared circuit observables relative to fair point/reduced-neuron baselines.\ndocs/milestones.md:154: It should add distributed, morphology-bound intraneuronal state and nothing else that can trivially explain the result.\ndocs/milestones.md:173:* **Strong:** the shared-readout change shrinks or disappears when morphology or synapse topology is shuffled  \ndocs/milestones.md:187:* split view showing baseline scalar activity versus surface-state activity on morphology  \ndocs/milestones.md:345:* both of you can explain why this boundary is sufficient for the first morphology-sensitive test  \ndocs/milestones.md:440:## Milestone 5 — Build the geometry ingestion and multiresolution morphology pipeline\